body: The file https://onnxruntimetestdata.blob.core.windows.net/models/20191107.zip  only contains public models from ONNX model zoo and TF slim models: https://github.com/tensorflow/models/tree/master/research/slim . Now it is not used in our build pipelines. The test data was about 30GB, and we have over 50 build jobs for each PR, which means need to download 1.5TB data for each PR iteration.  Instead,  now I preinstall the test data and models to our build machines, so that we don't need to download the huge file in every build pipeline run.

Could you provide alternative for other people, not just your CI machine, to use?
We rely on ort's unit tests to validate our build, for both correctness, linkage, permission, path, ...
The removal of data completely blocks 3rd-party from running ort tests.
Or maybe your script for packaging that zip file? We can pull from public zoo instead, actually that's better, but we want to make sure we're fully align with whatever assumption/layout you have.
I don't have any script for doing that.

So did you manually put together that?
Any way we can recreate (at least a subset of) that?
It was a shared folder. Many engineers wrote data into it, in a manual way.

So can we have some way to allow people outside of ort/microsoft get unit test data? Or there'll be a big gap for whoever trying to build ort themselves.

Feel free to include PM here if you think it's a feature request rather than a big fix.
IMHO this is a critical feature for an open-source lib.

We can distribute onnxruntime source code and binary, but we can't redistribute the other one's models as they are not made by us. 
And I can't make internal models public.  Please think how I can satisfy both of the following needs:
1. Validate each change in ORT to make sure it would not break @xkszltl 's in-production model
2. Share the models to everyone

Maybe there're some misunderstanding here.
I never asked for private model, and didn't expect to guard the code quality by downstream use case.
What I'm asking for is the public data required for CI/unit testing, i.e. a way to run ctest.
